Leadership from all three groups outlined what they investigate, how investigations are conducted, and how many staff members they have to investigate. Each unit reported relatively small staffing levels given the size of the programs they oversee.

The Division of Audit currently employs 24 people. The Fraud Investigation and Recovery Unit has 15 investigators, while the MaineCare Program Integrity Unit has 11 staff members. Lawmakers questioned whether those staffing levels are adequate to handle the workload.

Tony Madden, deputy director of the Division of Audit, said that any team would want additional staff.

“I think we're doing the best we can with the personnel that we have,” Madden said. “It's been a difficult hiring process to maintain the amount of qualified people that we have in the office.”

Bill Logan, who oversees the MaineCare Program Integrity Unit, told lawmakers his team is responsible for monitoring more than 5,200 MaineCare providers statewide. Not all of those providers actively bill the program, he said, noting that some may be out-of-state hospitals or providers that only bill occasionally.

“Like a dentist, or another MaineCare provider,” said Logan. “There are a lot.”

Logan said his unit relies on eight analysts to review billing activity and identify potential concerns among those thousands of providers.

Each of the three DHHS oversight groups also shared data on how many investigations they conduct each year. While the numbers varied from unit to unit, officials said those figures are consistent with what they have seen in recent years.

